{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A request whose signature does not match its body is rejected with a 401 response; the body is not forwarded.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is handler↔queue interaction plus signature verification, not just a pure HMAC helper. MOCK-MISS: could pass unit tests of verifier while still forwarding due to wiring bug. REAL-INFRA/LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP are not required by the behavior text. Rejected higher level: behavior says only HTTP status and forwarding decision; no requirement for real network/OS or AI output.","test_description":"Start the handler in-process with a test queue adapter that records enqueues. Send a request object with invalid `X-Signature-256` over a local test harness, assert `401`, and assert zero enqueue calls.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"An event is written to the persistent queue before the HTTP 200 acknowledgment is returned to the sender.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is an ordering/awaiting bug at module handoff (handler→persistent queue). MOCK-MISS: unit-testing a single function misses async ordering defects. REAL-INFRA not strictly required: a controllable queue implementation in-process can prove response is blocked until write resolves. Rejected System: behavior does not require real network/OS primitives, only write-before-ack ordering.","test_description":"Wire handler with the real queue module (or a controllable integration double that exposes write resolution timing). Delay queue write completion, verify no `200` is emitted before write resolves; then resolve and assert `200`.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The handler returns the HTTP response without waiting for downstream processing of the event to finish.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Behavior targets decoupling between enqueue/ack path and downstream worker path. Failure appears when modules interact (handler, queue, processor). REAL-INFRA is not required; in-process delayed processor is enough. Rejected System: text does not require real HTTP network behavior, only non-blocking orchestration.","test_description":"Use in-process server harness with a downstream processor stub that blocks on a promise. Send valid event, assert response is returned before processor promise resolves, and event was enqueued.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.82,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The response arrives within 3 seconds wall-clock time even when downstream processing of earlier events is slow and concurrent.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"REAL-INFRA dominates: wall-clock SLA under concurrency depends on runtime scheduling, actual HTTP serving, and contention effects that fakes can hide. MOCK-HIDE: mocked timing/subsystems may pass while real server misses 3s under load. Rejected Integration: behavior explicitly requires wall-clock timing with concurrent slow prior events, which is an OS/runtime-level effect.","test_description":"Run the real Node HTTP server process and real queue/worker wiring. Seed slow concurrent earlier events, then issue a new valid webhook via real HTTP client; measure end-to-end wall-clock and assert response < 3s.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.18,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"An event whose ID was already received is not written to the queue a second time.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Dedup correctness is a cross-module state behavior (handler + queue persistence/uniqueness). Unit tests of ID-check helpers can miss race/state propagation issues. No real network/OS primitive is required beyond local persistence. Rejected System: behavior text is about duplicate write prevention, not real network/subprocess behavior.","test_description":"With handler plus persistent queue store in test environment, send two requests with same event ID. Assert first is accepted/enqueued and second is not enqueued (idempotent outcome), including persisted state check.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.84,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"When the queue reports it is full, the handler returns 503 with a Retry-After header.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary failure boundary is error propagation/mapping from queue module to HTTP response. MOCK-MISS: unit test of status-mapping logic alone can miss wiring of queue-full signal. Rejected System: behavior says 'queue reports it is full' (not that capacity must be physically reached here), so real infrastructure is not required for this specific behavior.","test_description":"Inject queue module that returns a canonical `QueueFull` error. Send valid request and assert HTTP `503` plus `Retry-After` header and no downstream dispatch.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"The persistent queue actually enforces its configured capacity limit and rejects events that would exceed it.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This verifies real queue component behavior with its persistence backend/config, beyond handler logic. Needs multiple modules (queue logic + storage/config), but not real external network/subprocess. Rejected System: text focuses on queue capacity enforcement semantics, which can be validated with local DB/filesystem integra